{"title":"10 winter training mistakes (and how to avoid them)","link":"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/fitness-and-training/winter-training-mistakes/","date":1612357200000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><section itemprop=\"articleBody\"><p><span>If you’re looking to get the most out of your winter training, then you’re already going to be head and shoulders above those cyclists who go into hibernation come autumn, only to return once the temperature is back in double digits.</span></p><p><span>That head start gives you the opportunity to put the building blocks in place for next year, whether building your fitness with long <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/fitness-and-training/base-training-cycling/\">base training</a> rides, </span><span>putting together a </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/fitness-and-training/how-to-plan-your-winter-training/\"><span>winter training plan</span></a><span>, or </span><span>making the most of the </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/fitness-and-training/indoor-cycling-benefits/\"><span>benefits of indoor cycling.</span></a></p><p><span>Winter can be a tough time to be a cyclist — and that’s just the challenging conditions on the roads and trails – but that doesn’t mean you should give up.</span></p><p><span>Here are 10 training mistakes to avoid – and how you can overcome them.</span></p><h2><span>Not having the right kit</span></h2><p><span>First thing’s first, having the right kit is essential to surviving winter on the bike. While your bravery is admired if you’re still riding in a pair of <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-cycling-shorts/\">bib shorts</a> and a short-sleeve <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-cycling-jerseys/\">cycling jersey</a> in winter, at best you’re going to get cold, at worst you may pick up an illness or get hypothermia.</span></p><p><span>A pair of </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/features/best-winter-bib-tights-for-cycling/\"><span>bib tights</span></a><span> should be a wardrobe staple come this time of year to keep the worst of the cold weather off your legs, while your top-half choice will depend on the conditions – from a <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-autumn-cycling-clothing/\">long-sleeve jersey</a> on milder days through to a windproof and </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-waterproof-jackets-for-cyclists/\"><span>waterproof jacket</span></a><span> for when things get really bad.</span></p><p><span>Covering your hands and feet with </span><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-cycling-gloves-for-winter-riding/\"><span>winter gloves</span></a><span> and <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-overshoes/\">overshoes</a> respectively will also keep your extremities warm, while a cap will keep the chill off your head.</span></p><div><picture><source media=\"(max-width: 320px)\" data-srcset=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/12/CP-005-17-01-18-Robert-Smith-2018_preview-a8cb206-e1575392915182.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=90&amp;resize=298%2C199, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/12/CP-005-17-01-18-Robert-Smith-2018_preview-a8cb206-e1575392915182.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=45&amp;resize=598%2C399 2x, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/12/CP-005-17-01-18-Robert-Smith-2018_preview-a8cb206-e1575392915182.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=45&amp;resize=897%2C599 3x, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/12/CP-005-17-01-18-Robert-Smith-2018_preview-a8cb206-e1575392915182.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=45&amp;resize=1197%2C799 4x\" type=\"image/webp\"><source media=\"(max-width: 320px)\" data-srcset=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/12/CP-005-17-01-18-Robert-Smith-2018_preview-a8cb206-e1575392915182.jp